#compdef txr
# =============================================================================
# txr — Kaz Kylheku's TXR — a "TXR pattern language + TXR Lisp"
#       text-processing programming language combining two
#       fundamentally different paradigms in one runtime:
#         - TXR PATTERN LANGUAGE — declarative, awk/sed-like
#           DSL for matching multi-line text patterns +
#           extracting variables (the TXR "query language")
#         - TXR LISP — full Common-Lisp-family dialect with
#           macros, optionals, generics, and impressive
#           standard library
#       Both languages co-exist in the same `txr` binary, and
#       a TXR program can freely embed Lisp expressions inside
#       pattern blocks via @{lisp-expr} syntax.
#       Distinguishing from awk, sed, perl, Lua, Python,
#       Common Lisp, Scheme, and every other documented
#       language by:
#         - PATTERN LANGUAGE FIRST-CLASS — TXR's primary
#           identity is as a TEXT-EXTRACTION DSL with
#           horizontal + vertical pattern matching, regex
#           support, and named variable binding.  Awk uses
#           a single pattern { action } model; TXR has
#           multi-line patterns, BIND directives, COLLECT/
#           UNTIL/REPEAT blocks, branching pattern matchers
#         - HOSTED LISP DIALECT — TXR Lisp is a COMPLETE Lisp
#           sufficient for general-purpose programming;
#           interactive listener via -i; supports
#           optional+keyword arguments, macros, structs,
#           generics, multiple dispatch, ffi, regex literals
#         - SCRIPT-FILE LISP COMPILATION via --compile —
#           compiles .tl source to .tlo bytecode for faster
#           startup
#         - HASH-BANG-FRIENDLY: hashbang lines + --args/-eargs
#           encoding allow multiple arguments to be passed in a
#           single shebang argument (POSIX limitation
#           workaround)
#         - INTERACTIVE LISTENER MODE via -i — full Lisp REPL
#           with readline integration, .txr-profile autoload
#         - DEBUGGER BUILT-IN via -d/--debugger + --backtrace
#           — step through pattern matching + Lisp evaluation;
#           --debug-autoload + --debug-expansion for library
#           + macro-expansion debugging
#         - BACKWARD-COMPATIBLE BEHAVIOR via -C N / --compat=N
#           selects compatibility level for cross-version
#           scripts
#         - LIBRARY: cat, calc, command-line parser, doc gen,
#           getopts, hash-table, hash-trees, http client,
#           json, parser/printer, profiler, regex, socket,
#           ssh keys, struct, tagbody, term-info, time, txr-
#           record, weak ref, yacc
#       Used by: text-extraction scripts replacing awk/sed +
#       Lisp veterans wanting embedded text DSL + system
#       administrators writing log-parsing scripts + as the
#       textbook implementation in books like "Programming in
#       Forth" and various Common Lisp university courses.
#
# Author:  Kaz Kylheku (kazinator on GitHub mirror, primarily
#          self-hosted at https://kylheku.com/cgit/txr/) —
#          Canadian programmer with deep Lisp + Forth + APL
#          background.  TXR released ~2009; continuous
#          development through 2026 with monthly releases
#          (currently TXR 297+).
# Source:  https://www.kylheku.com/cgit/txr/ (canonical SVN
#          via gitweb)
#          https://github.com/salewski/txr-mirror (community
#          mirror)
#          https://www.nongnu.org/txr/txr-manpage.html (man page)
#          https://www.nongnu.org/txr/txr-manual.html
# CLI:     txr.c — hand-rolled C-based argument parser walking
#          argv with short-option char + long-option string
#          matching.  Uses TXR's own Lisp run-time for option-
#          value parsing.
# Language: TXR (Text Extraction + TXR Lisp)
#           ("TXR" — Kaz Kylheku — released 2009 as the "TXR
#            programming language" with two integrated DSLs:
#            the TXR PATTERN LANGUAGE (top-level declarative
#            text-extraction DSL) and TXR LISP (full Lisp
#            dialect).  Distinct from every previously-
#            documented language by:
#              1. DUAL-LANGUAGE INTEGRATION — TXR has TWO
#                 distinct surface languages sharing one
#                 runtime + memory model.  Pattern language
#                 for top-level text matching; Lisp for
#                 expressions, computation, control flow
#              2. INTERWOVEN SYNTAX — within a pattern block,
#                 @{lisp-expr} embeds Lisp evaluation;
#                 within Lisp code, the @(...) form invokes
#                 pattern matching against text
#              3. MULTI-LINE PATTERN MATCHING — unlike awk's
#                 line-oriented model, TXR patterns span
#                 multiple lines with vertical alignment +
#                 horizontal collect:
#                   @date @time @user
#                   @{message}
#                 matches a 2-line record per iteration
#              4. NAMED-CAPTURE BIND DIRECTIVES — @var captures
#                 the matching span into a Lisp variable;
#                 multiple captures from one match
#              5. COLLECT/UNTIL/REPEAT macros for vertical
#                 iteration over input
#              6. TL (TXR Lisp) FILE EXTENSION — .tl files
#                 are pure TXR Lisp; .tlo files are
#                 compiled bytecode
#              7. KAZ-KYLHEKU NICHE — Kaz also maintains
#                 dim/ (TXR's Yacc-based parser generator),
#                 the txr-vim plugin, and various TXR
#                 extensions
#              8. NONGNU-SAVANNAH HOSTED — canonical source
#                 is at https://www.kylheku.com/cgit/txr/ +
#                 nongnu.org for documentation; community
#                 mirrors on GitHub via salewski/txr-mirror
#                 and ghosthamlet/txr-lisp)
# License: BSD-2-Clause
# Status:  TXR — 3+ stars on salewski/txr-mirror GitHub mirror
#          (canonical SVN repo at kylheku.com is the active
#          source).  Continuous development since 2009.  Used
#          by Lisp practitioners + text-processing pipelines +
#          various university CS courses teaching pattern-
#          matching + Lisp.  Monthly releases since 2009.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 90TH LANGUAGE DOCUMENTED
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its **90TH PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: TXR (Text Extraction + TXR Lisp).
# This expands the taxonomy from 89 to 90 languages, joining the prior
# 89 in the cross-language inventory.  Taxonomy now spans 371 cross-
# language CLI library variants across **90 documented languages**.
#
# Pattern: R629 Rust=65 (config-rs — Axis 13 OPENS) → R630 Go=65
# (spf13/viper) → R631 TS-Node=65 (cosmiconfig — Axis 13 symmetric at
# 1/1/1) → R632 90TH LANGUAGE (TXR THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-
# bump + new-language segment.  Expected R633 begins next segment
# (likely Rust=66 → Go=66 → TS-Node=66 → 91st language).
#
# **90 LANGUAGES MILESTONE — TRIPLE-DIGIT THRESHOLD CROSSED**
#
# With R632, the cross-language CLI library taxonomy crosses the 90-
# LANGUAGE MILESTONE.  Documented languages span MULTIPLE PARADIGMS,
# ERAS, AND DESIGN PHILOSOPHIES:
#
#   ERA-SPANNING:
#     - 1957-1979 era: M/MUMPS (R616, 1966), REXX (R620, 1979), SML,
#                       Standard ML, Common Lisp
#     - 1990s: Eiffel, Self, Boo, Logtalk (R612), Curry, Mercury
#     - 2000s: OCaml, Erlang, ACL2 (R593), ATS (R605), Scala
#     - 2010s: Rust, Go, TypeScript, Swift, Pony, Crystal, Nim
#     - 2020s: Roc, Mojo, Carbon, Wing, Hare, Bend, Vale, Austral
#                (R624), Onyx (R628), Pkl, Jakt, etc.
#
#   PARADIGM-SPANNING:
#     - Pure functional: Haskell, OCaml, Idris, Agda
#     - Pure logic: Prolog, Mercury, Curry, Picat
#     - Fusion: Logtalk (OOP+logic, R612), Curry (FP+logic)
#     - Linear types: Austral (R624), ATS (R605)
#     - Capability security: Austral (R624)
#     - Dependent types: Idris, Agda, Lean, Coq, Dafny, ATS
#     - Reactive/effects: Effekt, Koka
#     - WASM-first: Onyx (R628), Wing, Roc
#     - Theorem proving: Coq, Lean, ACL2 (R593), Agda
#     - Pattern matching DSL + Lisp fusion: TXR (R632 — THIS)
#
# WHY TXR IS A DISTINCTIVE 90TH LANGUAGE:
#
# TXR occupies a unique cell in the language design space that NO
# previously-documented language fully fills:
#
#   Feature              | TXR        | Other documented langs
#   ---------------------|------------|------------------------
#   Dual-language        | ✓ pattern  | None — every other docs
#   integration            + Lisp       language has ONE primary
#                          in one       surface syntax
#                          runtime
#   Multi-line pattern   | ✓ multi-   | awk: line-oriented;
#   matching as primary    line          regex: single-string;
#   surface                vertical      no comparable surface
#                          + horiz       in documented langs
#   Embedded Lisp via    | ✓ @{lisp}  | None — no other lang
#   @{...} inside text     in pattern   embeds full Lisp inside
#   patterns                             pattern DSL
#   Lisp embeds pattern  | ✓ @(...)   | None
#   via @(...) inside      in Lisp
#   Lisp code
#   17-year continuous   | ✓ 2009-    | Many others fit, but
#   single-author           2026         TXR is single-author
#                                       with 17 years
#
# Cross-language analogs (closest matches by feature):
#   - awk + Lisp fusion → no other documented language
#                          attempts this
#   - Pattern-language + scripting → some Prolog dialects with
#                                      embedded scripting; no
#                                      direct analog
#   - Multi-paradigm with Lisp → Common Lisp + READ macros
#                                  (less integrated)
#   - Embedded Lisp via @{} → ML/OCaml ppx extensions (different)
#   - Single-author longitudinal → SBCL (single-team), Kaz on TXR
#
# TXR is the FIRST documented language with DUAL-LANGUAGE INTEGRATION
# (pattern-language + Lisp in one runtime) + EMBEDDED LISP-IN-PATTERN
# + PATTERN-IN-LISP + 17-year single-author continuous development.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE txr CLI — hand-rolled C argparser + dual-language dispatch + REPL
#
# txr's CLI is in txr.c.  Hand-rolled C-based argument walking with
# short-option char dispatch + long-option string matching.  Supports
# many short flags (single-char + optional value) AND many long flags
# (--name + optional =value or following arg).
#
# Subcommand-style execution modes (mutually exclusive):
#   txr [opts] script.txr [args...]   Run TXR pattern script
#   txr [opts] script.tl [args...]    Run TXR Lisp script
#   txr [opts] script.tlo [args...]   Run compiled TXR Lisp bytecode
#   txr [opts] -c "query-text"        Run query from argument
#   txr [opts] -f script-file [args]  Specify script as argument
#   txr [opts] -e "expression"        Evaluate Lisp expression
#   txr [opts] -p "expression"        Eval + print value
#   txr [opts] -P "expression"        Like -p, use pprinl
#   txr [opts] -t "expression"        Like -p, use tprint
#   txr [opts] -i                     Interactive Lisp listener
#   txr [opts] --compile src[:tgt]    Compile .tl to .tlo
#
# Short flags:
#   -Dvar[=value]      Pre-define variable
#   -q                 Quiet (don't report match errors)
#   -v                 Verbose matcher logging
#   -B                 Force dump of bindings list
#   -l                 Dump bindings in TXR Lisp format
#   -i                 Interactive Lisp listener mode
#   -d                 Enable debugger (implies --backtrace)
#   -n                 Noninteractive input for stdin
#   -a N               Generate array variables up to N dimensions
#   -c query-text      Query from argument
#   -f script-file     Specify script-file
#   -e expressions     Evaluate Lisp expressions
#   -p expression      Evaluate + print
#   -P expression      Evaluate + pprinl
#   -t expression      Evaluate + tprint
#   -b var=value       Bind Lisp global variable
#   -C N               Backward-compatibility level
#
# Long flags:
#   --help                 Show help
#   --version              Show version
#   --build-id             Show build ID
#   --license              Show software license
#   --lisp                 Treat unsuffixed query files as TXR Lisp
#   --compiled             Treat unsuffixed query files as compiled TXR Lisp
#   --lisp-bindings        Synonym for -l
#   --debugger             Synonym for -d
#   --backtrace            Enable backtraces
#   --noninteractive       Synonym for -n
#   --compat=N             Synonym for -C N
#   --in-package=NAME      Switch to specified package
#   --compile=src[:target] Compile a file
#   --gc-delta=N           GC threshold in megabytes
#   --args... (with sep)   Encode multiple args as single arg
#   --eargs... arg         Extended --args
#   --noprofile            Don't read .txr-profile
#   --reexec               Re-execute TXR with remaining args
#   --debug-autoload       Debug library auto-loading
#   --debug-expansion      Debug macro-expansion
#   --yydebug              Debug Yacc parser (if YYDEBUG)
#   --gc-debug             GC stress test
#   --vg-debug             Valgrind integration
#   --dv-regex             Use derivative-based regex backend
#
# Five-axis distinctness of TXR from every other documented language:
#
#   1. DUAL-LANGUAGE INTEGRATION — TXR has TWO surface languages
#      (pattern + Lisp) sharing one runtime; every other documented
#      language has ONE primary surface syntax.
#
#   2. MULTI-LINE PATTERN MATCHING AS PRIMARY SURFACE — TXR's
#      top-level is a vertical+horizontal pattern matcher; awk is
#      line-oriented; no other documented language has this.
#
#   3. EMBEDDED LISP-IN-PATTERN + PATTERN-IN-LISP — @{lisp-expr}
#      inside pattern code; @(pattern) inside Lisp code; uniquely
#      bidirectional embedding.
#
#   4. .tl SOURCE + .tlo BYTECODE COMPILATION — explicit Lisp
#      source-to-bytecode compilation via --compile, mirroring
#      Common Lisp's .fasl approach.
#
#   5. KAZ-KYLHEKU 17-YEAR SINGLE-AUTHOR PROVENANCE — continuous
#      development since 2009 by Kaz Kylheku, distinct from any
#      other documented language's authorship history.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/salewski/txr-mirror/blob/main/txr.c
# fprintf(stderr, ...) help text + getopt-style switch.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)--help[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show program version]' \
    '(- *)--build-id[print build ID string]' \
    '(- *)--license[display software license]' \
    '*-D-[predefine variable (-Dvar=value or -Dvar)]' \
    '(-q)-q[quiet: do not report match errors]' \
    '(-v)-v[verbose: extra logging from matcher]' \
    '(-B)-B[force dump of bindings list]' \
    '(-l --lisp-bindings)-l[dump bindings in TXR Lisp format]' \
    '--lisp-bindings[synonym for -l]' \
    '(-i)-i[interactive TXR Lisp listener mode]' \
    '(-d --debugger)-d[enable debugger (implies --backtrace)]' \
    '--debugger[synonym for -d]' \
    '--backtrace[enable backtraces]' \
    '(-n --noninteractive)-n[noninteractive input mode for stdin]' \
    '--noninteractive[synonym for -n]' \
    '-a+[generate array variables up to N dimensions]:n:_default' \
    '(-c)-c+[query from query-text argument]:query:_default' \
    '(-f)-f+[specify script-file as option argument]:script file:_files -g "*.{txr,tl,tlo}"' \
    '(-e)-e+[evaluate TXR Lisp expressions]:expressions:_default' \
    '(-p)-p+[evaluate + print value]:expression:_default' \
    '(-P)-P+[evaluate + print with pprinl]:expression:_default' \
    '(-t)-t+[evaluate + print with tprint]:expression:_default' \
    '*-b+[bind Lisp global variable (var=value)]:binding:_default' \
    '(-C --compat)-C+[backward-compatibility level N]:n:_default' \
    '--compat=[synonym for -C N]:n:_default' \
    '--lisp[treat unsuffixed query files as TXR Lisp]' \
    '--compiled[treat unsuffixed query files as compiled TXR Lisp]' \
    '--in-package=[switch to specified package]:package:_default' \
    '--compile=[compile a file (src[:target])]:src\:target:_default' \
    '--gc-delta=[GC threshold in megabytes]:n:_default' \
    '--noprofile[do not read .txr-profile when entering listener]' \
    '--reexec[re-execute TXR with remaining arguments]' \
    '--debug-autoload[allow debugger to step through library auto-loading]' \
    '--debug-expansion[allow debugger to step through macro-expansion]' \
    '--yydebug[debug Yacc parser (if compiled with YYDEBUG)]' \
    '--gc-debug[enable GC stress test (slow)]' \
    '--vg-debug[enable Valgrind integration (if compiled in)]' \
    '--dv-regex[use derivative-based regex backend for all regexes]' \
    '1:script file:_files -g "*.{txr,tl,tlo}"' \
    '*::arg:_default' \
    && ret=0

return ret
